    </header>

    <section>
        <h2>Ingredients</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>1 pound ground pork</li>
            <li>2 cups napa cabbage, finely chopped</li>
            <li>2 green onions, finely chopped</li>
            <li>2 cloves garlic, minced</li>
            <li>1 tablespoon ginger, grated</li>
            <li>1 tablespoon soy sauce</li>
            <li>1 tablespoon sesame oil</li>
            <li>1 teaspoon sugar</li>
            <li>1/2 teaspoon salt</li>
            <li>1/4 teaspoon black pepper</li>
            <li>40 gyoza wrappers</li>
            <li>Water for sealing the wrappers</li>
            <li>Vegetable oil for pan-frying</li>
            <li>Soy sauce and rice vinegar for dipping</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Tags</h2>
        <ol>
            <li>Gyoza</li>
            <li>Japanese</li>
            <li>Dumplings</li>
            <li>Pork</li>
            <li>Appetizer</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Instructions</h2>
        <ol>
            <li>In a large bowl, mix together ground pork, napa cabbage, green onions, garlic, ginger, soy sauce, sesame oil, sugar, salt, and black pepper until well combined.</li>
            <li>Place a gyoza wrapper on a clean surface. Spoon a small amount of the pork mixture into the center of the wrapper.</li>
            <li>Dip your finger in water and moisten the edges of the wrapper. Fold the wrapper in half, creating a semicircle, and press the edges to seal the gyoza.</li>
            <li>Repeat the process until all the wrappers are filled.</li>
            <li>Heat vegetable oil in a pan over medium-high heat. Place the gyoza in the pan, flat side down, and cook until the bottoms are golden brown.</li>
            <li>Once the bottoms are browned, add water to the pan and cover immediately to steam the gyoza until cooked through.</li>
            <li>Remove the cover and let the gyoza continue cooking until the water has evaporated, and the bottoms are crisp again.</li>
            <li>Serve the gyoza hot with a dipping sauce made from soy sauce and rice vinegar.</li>
            <li>Enjoy your delicious homemade Gyoza!</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

